INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '48cb93aa-cb1d-4d25-b54a-c5ab71409fb6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$React Component Design: Split at the Seam, Not Arbitrarily$escape$,
  $escape$Every React component has two jobs fighting for space: fetching/transforming data and rendering UI. When they share a file, you get components that are hard to test, reuse, or reason about.

The split is simple: container components own state, effects, and data logic — they pass everything down as props. Presentational components are pure functions of props, no hooks beyond `useMemo`/`useCallback` for perf.

The 150-line rule is a smell detector, not a hard limit. A 200-line pure JSX component is fine. A 60-line component mixing `useEffect`, `fetch`, business logic, and render is already too coupled.

The real test: can you render your component in a Storybook story with just props? If you need to mock `fetch`, wrap it in a provider, or stub a context, your presentational layer has leaked logic.

Custom hooks are the extraction point. `useUserProfile()` returns `{ user, isLoading, error }` — the component consumes it. Now you can unit test the hook with `renderHook` and snapshot test the UI independently.$escape$,
  $escape$// Logic lives in the hook
function useUserProfile(id: string) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);
  const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState(true);
  useEffect(() => {
    fetchUser(id).then(setUser).finally(() => setIsLoading(false));
  }, [id]);
  return { user, isLoading };
}

// Component is a pure renderer
function UserCard({ id }: { id: string }) {
  const { user, isLoading } = useUserProfile(id);
  if (isLoading) return <Skeleton />;
  return <div>{user?.name}</div>;
}$escape$,
