INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ab060ca6-1b00-4e0c-94f7-5b46a9cc66d5',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Production Monitoring in React: Sentry, Web Vitals, and Source Maps$escape$,
  $escape$Sentry's React SDK wraps your app in an ErrorBoundary that captures uncaught exceptions with full component stack traces — not just JS call stacks. Pair it with `Sentry.withProfiler(App)` to get render performance data tied to real errors.

For Web Vitals, use the `web-vitals` package with `reportWebVitals` from Create React App — or call `onCLS`, `onLCP`, `onINP` directly in Vite setups — and pipe results into Sentry via `Sentry.captureMessage` with `level: 'info'` and metric data attached.

Source maps are critical: without them, Sentry shows minified stack traces. Configure your bundler to upload maps to Sentry during CI using `@sentry/vite-plugin` or `@sentry/webpack-plugin`. Set `SENTRY_AUTH_TOKEN` in your pipeline, enable `sourceMaps: { hidden: true }` so maps don't ship to the browser, and Sentry will automatically de-minify traces server-side. Never skip `release` tagging — it ties errors to the exact deploy that introduced them.$escape$,
  $escape$// main.tsx
Sentry.init({
  dsn: import.meta.env.VITE_SENTRY_DSN,
  release: import.meta.env.VITE_SENTRY_RELEASE,
  integrations: [Sentry.browserTracingIntegration()],
  tracesSampleRate: 0.2,
});

// Report Core Web Vitals to Sentry
import { onCLS, onLCP, onINP } from 'web-vitals';

const reportToSentry = ({ name, value, id }: Metric) =>
  Sentry.captureMessage(name, {
    level: 'info',
    extra: { value, id },
  });

[onCLS, onLCP, onINP].forEach(fn => fn(reportToSentry));$escape$,
